tip.text:
Have All Saints started doing cocktail bars? The Bonneville definitely has that vibe, with the shabby walls, ram skulls on the wall, and old school lighting. That curved stained glass ceiling up the back is freakin' gorgeous though, and we have to admit, the whole shabby Parisian feel of the place is a winner...particularly the fog they produce with dry ice.

Old school cocktails are on the menu too, like Mint Juleps, and the menu keeps things French with dishes like Ratatouille. The grub's not bad, but it's the feel of the joint that we love.

This underground cubby hole provides excellent seasonal cocktails, a small menu of tasty bites and some of the best quality sound this side of the Brandenburg Gate. Propping up the bar here reminds us of being in the kitchen at a house party - a particularly stylish one. It may be a squeeze, but you get the feeling you'll miss something truly great if you leave. It wouldn't be unusual to share a knowing smile with the DJ over some crisp electronic beats; or swap a joke with the bar staff while they cooly whip you up a blend of unknown spirits with genuinely inventive seasonal touches. This is a cocktail emporium of the most laid-back variety; a good time bar with exceedingly good taste.

If you’re wondering if this Breaking Bad-themed cocktail bar is all gimmick, we should say: it is. But it has enough attention to detail, enough interactivity, and enough cool shit going on that it transcends what could just exist as a clickbait FB video and becomes a place that we might actually recommend. The whole thing is built into an RV truck like the one from the show; you’ll don yellow safety suits, grab a welcome cocktail of crystal meth (a mojito in a flask with a syringe of blue liquid) and take a seat somewhere in the meth lab caravan. The menu takes you straight back to your GCSEs with Bunsen burners, test tubes, and neon-coloured alcoholic beverages.

The cocktails are a little sweet for our tastes but the fun here is the spectacle: using dry ice to create vanilla smoke to infuse our peach liquor with; using syringes and an electric pump to make white chocolate foam; and best/weirdest of all - a bowl of Kahlúa-milk Rice Crispies. It’s an experience, and for £35 quid for two hours and three cocktails, is just inside the realms of not a bump.

Outside of the RV they’ve got another bar, vegan pizzas, a pumping hip hop soundtrack, and arcade machines where you’ll be awarded a shot depending on your score. Oh, and the whole place is vegan. Seriously there’s a lot going on at this place, and we’re still trying to wrap our heads around it all. Or maybe we actually just took meth and this was all some fever-dream. Is anyone else itchy?

It may seem like everyone and their grandma is transforming an abandoned East End railway arch into something or other, but you can't fault Night Tales for their ambition. Set in two arches and an accompanying outdoor area that encompass almost 6,000 square feet, this is a huge Hackney hangout spot offering plenty. There's an Asahi beer garden, covered and heated seating areas, live music from a 300-capacity club space, a large cocktail bar, a beer shack, an in-house Japanese Izakaya restaurant (Fat Baby) and pizza (Sons of Slice).

They've battened down the hatches for winter, covering their huge covered terrace and adding some fire pits, candles and, fear not, dependable heaters pumping out warmth. Just don't think too much about that energy bill. Liable to get lively on weekend evenings, head here for a little hibernation, Hackney style.

Blonde sisters Verity and Sharmaine Cox have taken over an old money shop and redecorated. Stripping away the plaster board, they found the remains of an alleyway underneath, added a few neon lights and voilà, Clapton has a new cocktail bar.

The whisky sours are bang on the money and they make a strong but tasty rum punch. They have a beer garden open all year, movie screenings and you can even bring along your own records to play on the decks at their 'Crate Digger Takeover'.

We could spend all day in this incredible store. And, luckily, we can. A coffee shop and fully-stocked bar enable round-the-clock fun (parties, exhibitions, illustration classes and open-mic nights). This feels like the kind of venture you should support, a place with real soul.

You’ll find wow-inducing women’s clothing, shoes and accessories from 1900s–80s. It’s great for dresses and there are even some bridal bits. Expect an in-house tailor and seamstress specialising in vintage alterations and a personal shopper on hand too. Upstairs the men’s selection is slightly smaller but still cool. Come for the clobber, stay for the cocktails.

When you heard the chaps behind the Sebright Arms were opening up a restaurant you were excited, right? So were we. And our instincts were right because The Vincent is a very decent all-day brunch & cocktail spot perfect for doing a bit of indulging, offering a bit of a rarity in these parts: substantial bang for your buck.

In a calming wooden oasis featuring big teak lanterns and banana trees, this is a perfect hangover or lazy weekend affair. The menu spans from the healthy to the downright decadent, with classic breakfast offerings joined by stuff like veggie hash, fried chicken and waffle, and their famous bunsmith buns filled with fried chicken or cheeseburgers. But whatever you do, save some space for their waffle with berries and cream - we got it thinking we only wanted a bite, and before we knew it our plate was licked clean.

Remember that sexy menu at Peg + Patriot? Well we do. And so does Matt Whiley (aka The Talented Mr Fox) 'cause he put it together. He got a food waste shaped bee in his bonnet and decided to set up a cocktail bar that's all about reducing it. How? Using only sustainable ingredients, distilling, fermenting and brewing in an on-site 'lab' and waging war on straws.

You too can fight the good fight, in a more relaxed manner, by slurping on his seasonal cocktails. Think strawberry wine, lemon balm gin and whey, or the fresher carrot, hemp seed and liquorice. Soak it up with sourdough and homemade kohlrabi or pickled celeriac and truffle and you might as well be at a spa. Sort of.

Isreali-inspired Bernstein’s Bar is a slice of Tel-Aviv cool sitting on a corner of Chatsworth Road. This is an ideal place to take a seat (inside or on the pavement) and watch the Clapton cool cats pass whilst tucking into hearty Middle Eastern dishes; having a coffee; doing the lazy lunch dance; or dipping the beak in something strong and letting the evening take over.

Sourcing plenty of their bits locally, the cuisine here is the comforting chow of Israel and the Levant: fish, meat and cheese sharing boards alongside filling and tasty soups - the chicken stew is known to cure almost every illness known to man. Serving all sorts for all sorts, it’s another vibey spot to add to Clapton’s growing arsenal.

All the silver linings here with strong drinks, low lights and good times. This cosy, quaint and intimate little spot is located right around the corner from Hackney Empire and features your perfect East Laandan cocktail list, including a monthly rejig of the classic old fashioned.

Once you've chosen your poison from the witty (if a little try hard) menu, prepare to be impressed. We like a sherry heavy menu so went for the 'Sherry Woo Woo'. We're fully on board with making sherry cool again. Maybe that should be our new slogan.

Don’t fall for the 60s worker’s-cafe exterior - Jim’s is a modern brunching spot through and through, gimmicky warts and all. What some lesser publications might call ‘hipster’, gimmicks come by way of the Black Skulls, the motorcycle ‘lifestyle brand’ that have taken over the residence with leathers on the walls and motorbike parts dotted about. As much as we’d like to sneer, the aesthetic meshes quite well with the retro wood-panelled diner vibe.

From bircher muesli to juicy, pink double cheese burgers, this is an all-day dining affair, but for us it’s gotta be brunch, when classics like kedgeree, salt beef hash, and kippers come into play - all done with the kind of finesse you'd associate with a more formal setting. Wash it down with an expertly crafted bloody mary (read: strong) and you’ve got yourself a breakfast-lunch mash-up fit for a king - or at least the boss of a Hackney biker gang.

The unremarkable door leading to a dark flight of stairs next to the Spar on Chatsworth Road does little to prepare you for the eye-popping beauty that awaits at the top. You’ll enter into a dimly lit bar where speckled mirrors, a sweeping curved ceiling, copper pineapple bar lamps and plush, chesterfield benches will transport you through time and space to 1920s Hollywood, and a rendezvous with someone glamorous and seductive. Or that dude you met on Happn.

The art deco aesthetic continues into the theatre where an abundance of red velvet and extremely comfortable armchairs will settle you in nicely. The only risk is feeling so at home that you end up falling asleep - especially with the recommended carafe of Borough Wines’ malbec. £5 tickets on Monday’s ain’t bad either.

OK we've seen the look on your face. How can a pub be 100% vegan, you're wondering. Well it pretty much means that, wherever possible, all the trimmings (food, drinks, fixtures and fittings) are plant-based and sustainably sourced.

Food is seen to by Club Mexicana which means tacos, nachos and burritos piled high with guacamole, tomatillo salsa, sour cream, pink onions, pickled chillies, chimichurri, fresh lime and coriander. Sounds tingly and tasty right? Our fave was the tofish sandwich which went down a treat. Wash all that down with cask ales (without the fish bits), Beavertown beer, small batch wines and some tasty cocky Ts.

We also popped by for brunch and devoured some tangy, spicy chick'n waffles with chilli maple and bacon (as decadent as it sounds); a full Mexican breakfast with all the plant-based trimmings; some fried tortillas with cherries and cream; and more cocktails that we'd care to admit. It's very on trend, for sure, but it's got the flavour chops to back itself.

Kitchen closed on Mondays.

Helgi’s is like being in the sixties - minus the racism and the sexism. A time warp in the middle of London Fields, transporting you back to the Summer of Luuuuvvvvvv. A better time, filled with free love, psychotropic drugs and hippie garms. A welcome break from the Tinder hook-ups, ket and bucket hats that plague our millennial generation.

The bar is intimate, and the smell of incense wafts in the air. A vinyl player blasts out tunes from the 60s, whilst wavy, psychedelic projections cover the walls. To properly enjoy the vibe, a cocktail is needed, of course. Try the Alabama Slammer, a mix of sloe gin, whisky, Galliano and Cointreau topped with orange juice. Some might say mixing that much alcohol is a bad idea, but this is the 60s honey, and mixing all substances is to be encouraged.

No way are the vegan wizards behind The Brook about to sacrifice flavour in their pursuit of plant-based pleasure - this is as close to vegan junk food as we've found in London. It's a vegan tapas restaurant and cocktail bar; a suitably laid-back, friendly and DIY-chic space where vegans and curious non-vegans enter the doors to see what's next in the vegolution. The answer: pretty nice grub with a surprising and satisfying indulgence about it.

The tip is to share five or six of their tapas dishes between two - and let us point you towards the moreish sesame chick'n skewers; the bountiful and comforting jackfruit quesadillas; and a zingy lime and coconut dal. Portion sizes are not huge - and potentially a pound or two over what we'd like - but given the meticulous R&D and care gone into creating each dish, we're prepared to make allowances.

The cocktails here are also not a simple add-on. Their huge choice of converted classics and house specials are put on the same footing as the food - meaning that whilst hungry foodies frequent the front and tuck into the tasty bits, the bar area and tables at the back create an altogether looser vibe.

Tucked away behind Hackney’s Wilton Way, Wolfie’s is a teeny tiny, dog-friendly bar - there’s space for about 15 so we reckon it’s got to be E8’s smallest drinking hole. Luckily there's plenty of pavement overspill space in the summertime.

It's the perfect spot to enjoy a glass of biodynamic orange wine and a selection of charcuteries, but the cocktail list is banging too; we rate the White Wolfgroni, made with suze, gin and white vermouth. A masterclass in flattering lighting and artfully distressed decor, Wolfie’s is only open Thursday to Sunday evenings. Hot tip: pop down on Sundays for some candle-lit live music and good vibes.

It’s hard to sum up how much we rate this place - we even considered keeping it a secret, until we remembered the main purpose of our employment. In a space perfectly utilising the edgy-industrial surrounds of the railway arch it finds itself in, you'll find an audio-lounge, restaurant (with changing kitchen residencies), vinyl store and art bookshop.

While away the hours sipping on a something at the bar; nodding your nut at a Saturday record shop in-store from in-house record label BBE; or tucking into something delicious from their low-lit, chic restaurant space. You get the sense that this is more of a passion project than a flagrant money-maker - it's often fairly tranquil and we get the feeling that's how they like it. Oops.

This industrial-chic lounge bar and restaurant may look out of your wallet’s league, but on opening the menu you'll be in for a nice surprise.

Serving great value lunches (try the grilled mackerel salad with fennel and apple slaw for £7), dinners and cocktails around the clock, this is the kind of neighbourhood place you'll find yourself nipping back to regularly. It was the classic Tom Collins-inspired drinks menu with over 40 variations that got our heads turnings - go for the Cognac Blazer Collins for all the tastes of Christmas in one glass, minus the turkey.

Formerly the rather ramshackle London Fields Pub, this building has had a significant refurb to become Martello Hall: a three storey townhouse that serves as a cocktail bar, restaurant, workspace and on-the-go coffeehouse. Plenty of dough has been spent on the stripped-back decor and vintage furniture, and the result is a pretty swanky and classy joint.

Food wise, it's mostly Italian fare with sharing plates and a wood fire oven for delicious pizzas. We'd particularly recommend the Number 7, with roast squash & beetroot, ricotta, hazelnuts, beetroot pesto, mint and kale. Upstairs, you'll find a cosy lounge area with decks and a cocktail bar, which seems an ideal place to woo and be wooed as the night unfolds.

What else? You can hot desk here and work, and also grab coffee or sausage roll by the inch from their street hatch.

El Garito is so darn discreet you’re half expecting the bartender to give you a round of applause for finding it when you come through the door. It's a diminutive, angular nook that feels like it might have been a broom-closet before someone had the bright idea to turn it into a romantic lil' money maker. And it is romantic and very, very intimate - if you've got secrets you don't want strangers knowing, don't come here and let that tongue get loose.

Cocktails is the rub, and the menu is reassuringly short - five or six very different, strong concoctions to be enjoyed on a high stool, whilst appearing wistful. Dim, dark and cosy, it's got the special 'hidden gem' vibe that would make it ideal for the first or second date flex. We did spy the charcuterie but would probably tip just sticking to the drinks.
